ğŸ”¹ Buyer Personas: Fictional profiles of ideal customers, enriched with customer journey maps.

ÄÃ£ xem We began the ChessPa series of books with ChessPa in the Chess Adventure Park as the first one. The book teaches little kids (from 3 years onwards) on the names of the pieces, how they move and also the rules of the game. As the book reached more people, we also came up with 3 activity books to combine with the first book.

While we thought about the next book in the ChessPa series, we wanted to build something that would inspire the youngsters. That is how the concept of ChessPa INSPIRATION series was born. The ChessPa Inspiration series aims to tell the stories of the chess champions of India - to bring forth their journey to the kids in a fun and digestible way.

And it gives us immense pleasure that on 28th of January 2025 (Sagar's 35th birthday) we launched the first book in the ChessPa inspiration series - ChessPa meets Guki - the Golden Boy. It's a book based on the real life story of Gukesh. His journey from an inquisitive 6-year-old kid to becoming the World Champion at the age of 18. 

We hope that this book will inspire the future generations of young chess players from India and the world. The book is now available for pre-order for a special price of Rs.499 until the Tata Steel Chess 2025 tournament ends (2nd of Feb) for a special price of Rs.499/- The MRP of the book is Rs.799/- The book will be delivered to you around 15th of March 2025.

The book contains 52 high quality brilliantly illustrated pages that deal with the life story of Gukesh and there are also additional 20 pages that have the pictures of Gukesh in real life. The book will also have a poster of Gukesh which can be put up in your room and also a post card, where you can take autographs of Gukesh and top players whenever you meet them!

The book is made with a lot of love and care and the hope is that we will be able to do more books in the future with many of the stars of Indian chess!

Pre-order the book from here: https://chessbase.in/online-shop#!/ChessPa-Meets-Guki-The-Golden-Boy/p/723133752

PS: There is also the ChessBase India Big New Year Sale going on, on the entire shop of ChessBase India from 28th to 30th of January. (https://chessbase.in/news/Big-New-Year-Sale-2025)

ÄÃ£ xem Data Analysts / Engineers - WHERE 1=1 

What is your take on this? (Do you know what it is?)

The first handful of times I saw this, it was in Oracle views and I hated it... 
I thought it was a waste of space and just WHY?!

Then I thought more about it... WHERE 1=1 actually has some practical uses. 

When you write a sql statement for a pipeline that might need to be dynamic and have a different where clause depending on the situation it is a lot easier to concatenate " and customer_segement = 'Mid-Market' " instead of having to figure out if there is already a where clause at all. 

Another version of WHERE 1=1 I've seen over the years is WHERE 1=0... The first time I saw this was in a procedure in a create table statement... I was like um WHY!!! 

But this actually has a practical use as well. If you need to create another table like a temp table or something you can say 

CREATE TABLE STAGING.SALES_TRANSACTIONS as 
SELECT CUSTOMER_ID, TRANSACTION_ID, TRANSACTION_AMT, ETC... 
FROM SALES.TRANSACTIONS
WHERE 1=0

This will create the structure of the table exactly the same as the referenced table without putting any records in the new table. 

What creative workarounds have you seen?

Do you have tech debt that you are pushing to the side because you are afraid of the workarounds that were used and you don't know how to decipher them? Let me know!

title: ÄÃ£ xem Devastating news ğŸ˜”

ÄÃ£ xem Hello guys, small update that might be disappointing to some of you, it's a long explanation going into the technicalities of analytics on this website so skip if you don't care.

So I started multistreaming to YouTube in December as an experiment to see if it really is just a win-win.

There's a theory that if you are a consistent youtuber, going live on YouTube and saving vods is bad (unless you're literally too big or famous then who cares, like moistcritikal who you might've seen sparked a bit of a surge to YouTube livestreaming).

The reason for that is now YouTube begins to push your stream vods simultaneously alongside your main content. And unsurprisingly, not a lot of people are going to watch a whole 5 hour vod then go and watch the edited video a couple days later. Or they might click a vod, realise it's a raw 5 hour video then instantly click off, killing the watch time in the algorithm. Essentially, cannibalising your content. So people stop clicking on your content, meaning you're being recommended less, meaning you've been washua schmidt'd.

I haven't done anything new or special except stop streaming on YouTube this month and I can already see that for the exact same style of content, some videos are performing upwards of 50% better than last month when I was going live daily AND uploading daily.

Some of this could be due to the fact that a lot of my live content naturally turns into videos so you have no reason to click the vod AND subsequent video, unlike others (best example, moist), whose YouTube and stream content is almost always entirely different from one another. Other variables could be the holiday season where people don't have as much time to watch (but also, some people DO have more time?). It could be that my content specifically isn't as diversified between stream and YouTube. It could be that vods and videos need to be spread out more and not done on the same day. Lots of factors could be at play here.

For this month, I've decided to stop streaming to YouTube, just to see how things go numbers wise on the regular uploads and series and to see if that really changes anything.

It might be that I bring back Farfa VODs and stream there instead in the future but for this moment in time, I think I want to just focus on creating YouTube content separate from streams and see what this does for my algo. I'll reassess the situation in February and might even do a deep dive in a video as a fun side project to figure out what's going on.

Anyway, long winded update to say

TL;DR, not streaming on YouTube this month to test if that's why my views are now up compared to last month for very similar content.

title:
ÄÃ£ xem ğŸ”¥ Hot Take: SQL Where FormattingğŸ§¨ 

When it comes to formatting SQL it seems like everyone has an opinion... 

Comma before or after the field name
Don't Use Select * for anything vs It's ok for Subqueries/CTEs
Indent your ON clauses for joins

I can go on and on.. 

Today though I want to mention Group By clause formatting. There are two different ones I want to point out.

My personal preference ... Column Names: 
`
GROUP BY Shift
 ,ServiceGrade
 ,Date 
`




Versus Numbered columns: 
`
GROUP BY 1,2,3
`




I've seen both methods over my several decade career and I could never bring myself to like the numbered columns. 



What do you think? Do you like the numbered columns? Do you like another format altogether? Share your opinion in the comments and let me know!



Happy Friday! Remember today is No Prod Friday save those production pushes until Monday if you don't want to work this weekend!
